Three absorption peaks at 248, 400, and 532 eV that are caused by C1s, N1s, and O1s can be seen in the XPS spectra of CDs-W and CDs-IL (Fig. 3
                        ), and their atomic percentage is given in Table 1
                        . The spectrum of C1s (Fig. 3a) of CDs-IL shows six absorption peaks at 286.1, 284.9, 284.3, 283.8, 283.4, and 282.9 eV, which are attributed to O–C]O (7.1%), C]O (15.1%), C–O (26.9%), C–N (24.9%), C–C/C–H (18.4%), and C]C (7.5%) groups, respectively [90–92]. In the spectrum of N1s (Fig. 3b), CDs-IL shows four absorption peaks at 405.4, 400.7, 398.9, and 398.4, which are attributed to Nitro Ns (9.9%), graphitic Ns (5.8%), pyrrole Ns (57.4.7%), and pyridine Ns (26.7%), respectively [22]. Interestingly, the peak at 405.4 eV confirms the nitrate N–O group on the surface [91]. In the spectrum of O1s (Fig. 3c, f), both CDs exhibit three absorption peaks at 530.5, 531.7, and 532.3 eV, which are due to C–O (13.2%), C]O (62.2%), and HO–C]O (24.4%), which supports the FTIR results [93]. CDs-W also shows six absorption peaks (Fig. 3d) at 286.2, 284.9, 284.3, 283.8, 283.3, and 282.8 eV, which are due to O–C]O (7.4%), C]O (14.7%), C–O (23.1%), C–N (23.3.1%), C–C/C–H (20.9%), and C =C (10.5%) groups, respectively [91,92]. N1s (Fig. 3e), CDs-W shows four absorption peaks at 399.0, 398.2, and 397.4, which are attributed to graphitic Ns (46.0%), pyrrole Ns (36.3%), and pyridine Ns (17.5%), respectively [22].
